The Core Problem: The Telescoping Constructor
Imagine you are writing a program to build custom desktop computers. 
A computer has a few required components (CPU, RAM) and many optional components (Dedicated GPU, Bluetooth, Water Cooling, RGB Lighting).

Without a Builder, you usually end up with a "telescoping constructor"—a massive, overloaded list of constructors to handle every possible combination:

The Solution: The Builder Pattern
The Builder pattern solves this by extracting the object construction code out of the main class and moving it into a separate Builder object. 
Instead of passing everything at once, you call specific, clearly named methods step-by-step.
